# Frontend Framework Guidelines

This rule covers Next.js best practices, React 19 component architecture, and custom React hooks development.

## 🚀 Next.js Best Practices

### App Router & Routing
- Use the App Router for better performance and routing efficiency
- Implement proper caching strategies with the `"use cache"` directive
- Default to server-side fetching for dynamic content
- Ensure error handling in route handlers for robust applications
- Leverage the latest features from Next.js, such as React Server Components and streaming

### Development & Deployment
- Regularly check for the newest Next.js version and upgrade to experimental tools where it makes sense
- Use `bun` for package management when possible
- Implement proper SEO practices with metadata API
- Use Next.js Image component for optimized image loading
- Implement proper loading states and error boundaries

### Performance Optimization
```typescript
// Example: Optimized page with proper caching
import { cache } from 'react';

const getData = cache(async (id: string) => {
  const data = await fetch(`/api/data/${id}`);
  return data.json();
});

export default async function Page({ params }: { params: { id: string } }) {
  const data = await getData(params.id);
  
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{data.title}</h1>
      <p>{data.description}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Server Components Best Practices
- Use React Server Components (RSC) for improved server-side rendering
- Avoid unnecessary `'use client'` directives to keep components lightweight
- Fetch data directly in Server Components when possible
- Use Suspense boundaries for loading states

```typescript
// Good: Server Component with data fetching
import { Suspense } from 'react';
import { LoadingSkeleton } from '@/components/LoadingSkeleton';

async function DataComponent({ id }: { id: string }) {
  const data = await fetchData(id);
  
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{data.title}</h2>
      <p>{data.content}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

export default function Page({ params }: { params: { id: string } }) {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<LoadingSkeleton />}>
      <DataComponent id={params.id} />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

## ⚛️ React 19 Component Architecture

### Component Design Principles
- Use React Server Components (RSC) for improved server-side rendering
- Avoid unnecessary `'use client'` directives to keep components lightweight
- Integrate error boundaries to handle component failures gracefully
- Optimize rendering by monitoring Web Vitals performance metrics

### Performance Optimization
```typescript
import { memo, useMemo, useCallback } from 'react';

// Good: Memoized component with optimized callbacks
const OptimizedComponent = memo(({ items, onItemClick }: {
  items: Item[];
  onItemClick: (item: Item) => void;
}) => {
  const sortedItems = useMemo(
    () => items.sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name)),
    [items]
  );

  const handleClick = useCallback(
    (item: Item) => {
      // Perform optimizations here
      onItemClick(item);
    },
    [onItemClick]
  );

  return (
    <div>
      {sortedItems.map(item => (
        <ItemComponent
          key={item.id}
          item={item}
          onClick={handleClick}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
});
```

### Error Boundaries
```typescript
'use client';

import { Component, ReactNode, ErrorInfo } from 'react';
import { logger } from '@/lib/utils/logger';

interface Props {
  children: ReactNode;
  fallback?: ReactNode;
}

interface State {
  hasError: boolean;
  error?: Error;
}

export class ErrorBoundary extends Component<Props, State> {
  constructor(props: Props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { hasError: false };
  }

  static getDerivedStateFromError(error: Error): State {
    return { hasError: true, error };
  }

  componentDidCatch(error: Error, errorInfo: ErrorInfo) {
    logger.error('Component error caught by boundary:', {
      error: error.message,
      stack: error.stack,
      componentStack: errorInfo.componentStack,
    });
  }

  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) {
      return this.props.fallback || (
        <div className="error-boundary">
          <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
          <p>Please try refreshing the page.</p>
        </div>
      );
    }

    return this.props.children;
  }
}
```

### Component Architecture Patterns
```typescript
// Good: Component with proper separation of concerns
interface ComponentProps {
  data: DataType;
  onAction: (id: string) => void;
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary';
}

export function FeatureComponent({
  data,
  onAction,
  variant = 'primary'
}: ComponentProps) {
  // Business logic
  const processedData = useMemo(() => 
    processBusinessLogic(data), [data]
  );

  // Event handlers
  const handleClick = useCallback(
    (id: string) => {
      // Validation
      if (!id) return;
      
      // Analytics tracking
      trackEvent('component_action', { id, variant });
      
      // Execute action
      onAction(id);
    },
    [onAction, variant]
  );

  // Render logic
  return (
    <div className={`component component--${variant}`}>
      {processedData.map(item => (
        <ItemComponent
          key={item.id}
          item={item}
          onClick={handleClick}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## 🎣 Custom React Hooks

### Hook Guidelines
- **Purpose**: Encapsulate reusable stateful logic, especially for data fetching or complex UI interactions
- **Location**: Place custom hooks in the `apps/hooks/` directory
- **Naming**: Use the `use` prefix (e.g., `useAccounts.ts`)
- **Simplicity**: Keep hooks focused on a single responsibility

### Data Fetching Hooks
For fetching data from API endpoints, prefer using `useSWR`. Follow the guidelines outlined in [data-fetching.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/data-fetching.mdc).

```typescript
// Example: Custom data fetching hook
import useSWR from 'swr';
import { fetcher } from '@/lib/utils/fetcher';

interface UseAccountsReturn {
  accounts: Account[] | undefined;
  isLoading: boolean;
  error: Error | undefined;
  mutate: () => void;
}

export function useAccounts(): UseAccountsReturn {
  const { data, error, isLoading, mutate } = useSWR<Account[]>(
    '/api/accounts',
    fetcher
  );

  return {
    accounts: data,
    isLoading,
    error,
    mutate,
  };
}
```

### Custom Hook Templates

#### State Management Hook
```typescript
import { useState, useCallback } from 'react';

interface UseToggleReturn {
  value: boolean;
  toggle: () => void;
  setTrue: () => void;
  setFalse: () => void;
  setValue: (value: boolean) => void;
}

export function useToggle(initialValue: boolean = false): UseToggleReturn {
  const [value, setValue] = useState(initialValue);

  const toggle = useCallback(() => setValue(prev => !prev), []);
  const setTrue = useCallback(() => setValue(true), []);
  const setFalse = useCallback(() => setValue(false), []);

  return {
    value,
    toggle,
    setTrue,
    setFalse,
    setValue,
  };
}
```

#### Form Handling Hook
```typescript
import { useState, useCallback } from 'react';
import { z } from 'zod';

interface UseFormOptions<T> {
  initialValues: T;
  validationSchema?: z.ZodSchema<T>;
  onSubmit: (values: T) => Promise<void> | void;
}

export function useForm<T extends Record<string, any>>({
  initialValues,
  validationSchema,
  onSubmit,
}: UseFormOptions<T>) {
  const [values, setValues] = useState<T>(initialValues);
  const [errors, setErrors] = useState<Partial<Record<keyof T, string>>>({});
  const [isSubmitting, setIsSubmitting] = useState(false);

  const setValue = useCallback((key: keyof T, value: any) => {
    setValues(prev => ({ ...prev, [key]: value }));
    // Clear error when user starts typing
    if (errors[key]) {
      setErrors(prev => ({ ...prev, [key]: undefined }));
    }
  }, [errors]);

  const validate = useCallback(() => {
    if (!validationSchema) return true;

    try {
      validationSchema.parse(values);
      setErrors({});
      return true;
    } catch (error) {
      if (error instanceof z.ZodError) {
        const fieldErrors: Partial<Record<keyof T, string>> = {};
        error.errors.forEach(err => {
          if (err.path.length > 0) {
            fieldErrors[err.path[0] as keyof T] = err.message;
          }
        });
        setErrors(fieldErrors);
      }
      return false;
    }
  }, [values, validationSchema]);

  const handleSubmit = useCallback(async (e?: React.FormEvent) => {
    e?.preventDefault();
    
    if (!validate()) return;

    setIsSubmitting(true);
    try {
      await onSubmit(values);
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Form submission error:', error);
    } finally {
      setIsSubmitting(false);
    }
  }, [values, validate, onSubmit]);

  const reset = useCallback(() => {
    setValues(initialValues);
    setErrors({});
    setIsSubmitting(false);
  }, [initialValues]);

  return {
    values,
    errors,
    isSubmitting,
    setValue,
    handleSubmit,
    reset,
    validate,
  };
}
```

#### API Hook with Error Handling
```typescript
import { useState, useCallback } from 'react';
import { logger } from '@/lib/utils/logger';

interface UseApiReturn<T> {
  data: T | null;
  loading: boolean;
  error: string | null;
  execute: (...args: any[]) => Promise<T>;
  reset: () => void;
}

export function useApi<T>(
  apiFunction: (...args: any[]) => Promise<T>
): UseApiReturn<T> {
  const [data, setData] = useState<T | null>(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

  const execute = useCallback(async (...args: any[]) => {
    setLoading(true);
    setError(null);
    
    try {
      const result = await apiFunction(...args);
      setData(result);
      return result;
    } catch (err) {
      const errorMessage = err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'Unknown error';
      setError(errorMessage);
      logger.error('API call failed:', err);
      throw err;
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  }, [apiFunction]);

  const reset = useCallback(() => {
    setData(null);
    setError(null);
    setLoading(false);
  }, []);

  return {
    data,
    loading,
    error,
    execute,
    reset,
  };
}
```

## 🎯 Frontend Architecture Best Practices

### 🚨 CRITICAL: EDIT EXISTING FILES FIRST
**Before creating any new component, page, or utility:**

1. **Search thoroughly** for existing files with similar functionality
2. **Extend existing components** rather than creating new ones
3. **Modify existing pages** instead of duplicating structure
4. **Only create new files** when no existing file can serve the purpose

### Component Organization
```
components/
├── ui/              # Basic UI components (buttons, inputs, etc.)
├── shared/          # Shared business components
├── features/        # Feature-specific components
│   ├── auth/
│   ├── dashboard/
│   └── profile/
├── layout/          # Layout components
└── pages/           # Page-level components
```

**Remember: Always search these directories for existing components before creating new ones**

### Performance Guidelines

#### DO:
- Use React Server Components for data-heavy components
- Implement proper memoization with `memo`, `useMemo`, and `useCallback`
- Use Suspense boundaries for loading states
- Implement error boundaries for graceful error handling
- Optimize bundle size with dynamic imports
- Monitor Web Vitals and Core Web Vitals

#### DON'T:
- Overuse `useEffect` - prefer built-in React patterns
- Create unnecessary client components
- Skip error boundary implementation
- Ignore performance monitoring
- Use inline functions in render methods without memoization
- Forget to clean up subscriptions and timers

### Hook Best Practices

#### Creating Custom Hooks:
- Create dedicated hooks for specific data types (e.g., `useAccounts`, `useLabels`)
- The hook should typically wrap `useSWR`, handle the API endpoint URL, and return the data, loading state, error state, and potentially the `mutate` function from SWR
- Keep hooks focused on a single responsibility
- Use TypeScript for better type safety
- Include proper error handling and loading states
- Document complex hooks with JSDoc comments

#### Using Hooks Effectively:
- Follow the Rules of Hooks (only call at the top level, only from React functions)
- Use built-in hooks before creating custom ones
- Prefer composition over complex custom hooks
- Test hooks in isolation when they contain complex logic

By adhering to these guidelines, we ensure a consistent approach to frontend development with optimal performance and maintainability.